photo.description: Armorial binding of Jacques-Auguste de Thou (1553-1617) Pictured here: Spine with the device of Jacques-Auguste de Thou and the conjoint monogram "I A G" [i.e. Jacques Auguste Gasparde] combining the initials of his given name with that of his second wife, Gasparde de La Chastre. Until the death in 1601 of his first wife, Marie Barbançon, Thou used the conjoint monogram "I A M". photo.description: DURVAND_PINARD Sc. [Binder's stamp of Louise Pinard, daughter and successor of Lucien Durvand (1852-1924). Durvand established his workshop in Paris in 1890 in association with someone named Thiret; he bound as "Durvand-Thiret" until the beginning of the twentieth century, when Thiret drops out of the picture. photo.description: Above: Sr. Giacomo Brateolo [...] [Autograph.] Below: Ex Bibliotheca Jo: Bapt[ista]e Bianchi 1736. [Dated 18th-century ms. ownership inscription, possibly that of Giovanni Battista Bianchi, aka Giano or Jano Planco, Italian physician and author. Bianchi was born in Rimini and graduated from the University of Bologna in 1719. According to Paula Findlen, "There was virtually no subject -- medical, scientific, antiquarian, and literary -- that did not interest Bianchi and virtually no academic controversy on which he did not voice his opinion" ("Medicine, Pornography and Culture in Eighteenth-Century Italy" in Italy's Eighteenth Century, ed. P. Findlen et al. (Stanford: Stanford UP, 2009), p. 219). Appointed professor of anatomy at the University of Siena in 1741, Bianchi so antagonized his colleagues and students that in 1743, after a public mocking during Carnival, he fled the city. "The university superintendent Pompeo Neri was ultimately forced to publish an Ordinance that the Insults against Bianchi Absolutely Cease in March 1743 in order to entice the difficult anatomist back to his job" -- which he abandoned for good in 1744, fed up with the failure of the Sienese to recognize his talents (Findlen, p. 220). Rimini was more simpatico, granting him the title "noble citizen" upon his return, and Bianchi spent the remainder of his days there, working as a medical practitioner and scientific researcher (in 1755 he famously used electricity to resuscitate a dog), as well as the director of a secondary school. Established heading: Bianchi, Giovanni, 1693-1775] Penn Libraries call number: GC55 P5895 568o All images from this book

photo.description: Bookplate of the Säfstaholms Bibliothek with the initials GTB [=Gustaf Trolle-Bonde] at head of bookplate. Gustaf Trolle-Bonde (1773-1855) "the Blind Excellency" was a patron of the arts and collector of books and paintings. He inherited Säfstaholms in 1797 and rebuilt and redesigned large parts of the estate to house his growing art collection and library. The library was sold in 1920. The estate is now an art museum showcasing Swedish artists from the early 20th century. Established heading (NLS): Trolle-Bonde, Gustaf, 1773-1855 Penn Libraries call number: GrC Ar466 S21 1622 All images from this book
